titioners. Tax and spending limitations at all levels of government, combined with the unfolding effects of welfare reform and managed health care, have increasingly emphasized the need for the efficient and accountable administration of health and social services in the private and public sectors. This edition confronts issues raised by these developments, including budgetary allocation and staff management, the problems of worker burnout and safety, the changing demographics and growing diversity of the supervising workforce, evidence-based and licensure supervision, and performance appraisal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBusiness and EconomicsxEconomicsxGeneral. 0aBusiness and EconomicsxReference. 0aSocial sciencesxGeneral. 0aSocial servicexorganization and administration. 0aSocial workersxSupervision ofzUnited States. 0aSocial workersxSupervision of. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Services.2bisacsh1 aHarkness, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070982708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kadu1517640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231525398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231525398/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070982-7  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles